abstract: A monstrous hurricane bearing winds of up to 120 miles per hour bore down on the tiny archipelago of Bermuda today.
snippet: A monstrous hurricane bearing winds of up to 120 miles per hour bore down on the tiny archipelago of Bermuda today.
lead_paragraph: Amonstrous hurricane bearing winds of up to 120 miles per hour bore down on the tiny archipelago of Bermuda today as rains and wind began to lash the islands, knocking out electricity in some areas, and residents braced for worse.
headline_main: Hurricane Bears Down on Bermuda Islands
headline_print_headline: Hurricane Bears Down on Bermuda Islands

abstract: DELANEY--Floyd J., age 80, passed away on September 2nd in Summit, NJ. As an esteemed business owner for 53 years, he was a pioneer in the air conditioning and mechanical contracting trades. A distinguished and engaging gentleman, he was well-traveled and known to many, from heads of state to Nobel scientists. Floyd was a friend to everyone and loved by all. He converted to Judaism in 1994 and was a great friend to Israel. He was a patriarch in the true sense, not just to his own family. He is survived by his beloved wife Ariella, his children, Thorne, Douglas, Cathy, John, and his grandchildren, Kate, Annie, Max, Marjorie, Molly, Dylan, August, Adria, Margaret and Samuel. Services Thursday, 1:15pm, at ''The Riverside'', 76th St. and Amsterdam Ave.

CARL ALLEN AND FRIENDS, Sweet Rhythm, 88 Seventh Avenue South, above Bleecker Street, West Village, (212) 255-3626. Mr. Allen, the drummer, came up through the encouragement of bandleaders like Jackie McLean and Woody Shaw; he plays hard-charging post-bop. Tonight and tomorrow night at 8, 10 and midnight; $15 with a $10 food or drink minimum. (Ben Ratliff).

abstract: A selective listing by Times critics of noteworthy pop and jazz concerts in the New York metropolitan region this weekend. * denotes a highly recommended concert.    * ANTIBALAS, Southpaw, 125 Fifth Avenue, Park Slope, Brooklyn, (718) 230-0236. While the New Museum has a summerlong exhibition devoted to Fela Kuti, the Nigerian bandleader and political gadfly, the band Antibalas discovered his music years ago. It delivers a New York makeover to Fela's Afrobeat, the Nigerian funk propelled by burly saxophones, fierce percussion and righteous anger. Performing constantly around New York has given the band a combined tightness and relaxation, the assurance that they can sustain and expand a groove until everyone is dancing. And watching them pack more than a dozen musicians on a small stage is a show in itself. Two sets begin tonight at 9; admission is $12 (Jon Pareles).
